h3. Issue Summary
* This issue is affecting the group search for the new Workspace Settings UI. When searching for groups which contain an underscore in its name, such as "GROUP_EXAMPLE", the UI will populate correctly the number of groups that matched your query, however, the list will be empty.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # On the new UI, add a group that contains an underscore in its name, e.g. "GROUP_EXAMPLE";
 # On the groups' page, try searching for that group;

h3. Expected Results
* The group should be displayed in the results list;

h3. Actual Results
* Results list is empty;

h3. Workaround
 Currently, there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary
 * After the Workspace settings got updated, the *Update Repository Access* feature is not present anymore in the UI, meaning that if there are repositories missing in an Administrators group, users have to go through the process of identifying missing repositories and add them.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Access the *workspace settings*;
# Navigate to *User groups*;
# Edit a group;

h3. Expected Results
* There should be a method to easily identify missing repositories or simply update the group's access to all repositories in the workspace;

h3. Actual Results
* It is not possible to update the group's access to all repositories owned by the workspace;

h3. Workaround
 # Fetch the list of missing repositories from the following API endpoint
{code:java}
/!api/internal/workspaces/$workspaceSlug/groups/$groupSlug/add-repositories?fields=values.full_name{code}
 # Manually add them to the group's scope.

h3. Issue Summary
* As part of new [changes to the build status endpoint|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/bitbucket/bitbucket-api-changes-commit-status/], admins are no longer able to change build statuses through the API;

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a build with *User A*;
 # Try to update the build status through the API using *User B* which is an admin;

h3. Expected Results
 # The admin *User B* should be able to update the build status;

h3. Actual Results
 # The following message is displayed and the user is not able to update the build status:
{code}
{“type”: “error”, “error”:
{“message”: “Authenticated user is not the creator (UserA) of this build status.“}
{code}

h3. Workaround
* It is necessary to perform the update with the Creator of the build (UserA);

h3. Issue Summary
* When creating a repository and specifically telling Bitbucket not to use any README or .gitignore file template, the main branch setting won't be correctly populated on the repository settings, making the branch view redirect you to the src page.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a repository without any readme or .gitignore file;
 # Once the repo is created try to create a README or .gitignore file from the repository src view 
 !Screen Shot 2021-06-09 at 17.30.49.png|thumbnail! 
 # Commit the file;
 # Try to go to the branches view;

h3. Expected Results
* The branches page will be loaded;

h3. Actual Results
* Users are redirected to the src page;

h3. Workaround

In order to fix this issue on repositories that were already created, the following steps should fix this issue:
# Navigate to the repository settings;
# On *Repository Details*, click on the *Advanced* dropdown;
# On *Main branch*, select your main branch from the dropdown;
# Click save and refresh the settings page to ensure the main branch is correctly set;
# The *Branch* page will load normally now.

h3. Issue Summary
When attempting to use the SSH 2FA method, with the command below:
{code}
ssh git@bitbucket.org recovery_codes
{code}

The following error message is thrown:
{code}
{"type": "error", "error": {"message": "You cannot administer personal accounts of other users."}}
{code}

Or even, the request is successful but the recovery codes are missing in the response:
{code}
Your single-use recovery codes are

Once logged in, you should immediately visit
https://bitbucket.org/account/user/git/two-step-verification/
to add a new two-step device.
Thank you for using Atlassian Bitbucket.
{code}

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Set up an SSH key and 2FA on your account
 # On your terminal, run the following command, as described [here|https://support.atlassian.com/bitbucket-cloud/docs/enable-two-step-verification/]:
{code}
ssh git@bitbucket.org recovery_codes
{code}

h3. Expected Results
The recovery codes are correctly displayed on the terminal.

h3. Actual Results
The following error is thrown:
{code}
{"type": "error", "error": {"message": "You cannot administer personal accounts of other users."}}
{code}
Or the Recovery Codes are missing in the response body;

h3. Workaround

Currently, the only known workaround is to disable your account 2FA using the e-mail method described here, under "Disable two-step verification":
https://support.atlassian.com/bitbucket-cloud/docs/enable-two-step-verification/

h3. Issue Summary
* When deleting LFS files from personal workspaces which had already changed the workspace ID, UI presents a an error saying it was not possible to delete the file with a *404* error in the console:
* {code}{
  "type": "error",
  "error": {
    "message": "The requested repository either does not exist or you do not have access. If you believe this repository exists and you have access, make sure you're authenticated."
  }
}{code}

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Add an LFS file to a repository inside a personal workspace;
 # Change the workspace ID through the workspace settings;
 # Try to delete the LFS file;

h3. Expected Results
 * LFS file should be deleted;

h3. Actual Results
 * The DELETE request to the LFS API endpoint is made through the old workspace ID, causing a 404;

h3. Workaround
In order to delete the LFS files in this case, you will need to:
# Clone the repo locally;
# Grab the LFS oid for the file you want to delete {code}$ git lfs ls-files -l{code}
# Delete the file with our API endpoint {code}$ curl -user <credential:password> -X DELETE "https://api.bitbucket.org/internal/repositories/<workspace_id>/<repository_slug>/lfs/<OID>{code}

h3. Issue Summary
* Users are intermittently not being able to load the Pull Requests page with a 403 error code through the console;
* UI presents *Something went wrong* error message

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 * As this issue is happening intermittently, there are no steps to reproduce, as it only occurs on accessing the Pull Requests list page;

h3. Expected Results
* Page should be normally rendered;

h3. Actual Results
* Page intermittently throws a *Something went wrong* message with a 403 status code on the browser dev tools

h3. Workaround
Current workarounds for this issue are:
* Refreshing the page;
* Logging out and back in;
* Clearing cache and cookies;
